The '''Revised Trauma Score''' (RTS) is a physiologic scoring system, designed for use in based on the initial [[vital signs]] of a patient.<ref name="old">{{cite journal |author=Champion HR, Sacco WJ, Carnazzo AJ, Copes W, Fouty WJ |title=Trauma score |journal=[[Crit. Care Med.]] |volume=9 |issue=9 |pages=672–6 |year=1981 |month=September |pmid=7273818 |doi= |url= |accessdate=2012-07-24}}</ref> A lower score indicates a higher severity of injury.<ref name="tabers">{{cite book |author=Taber, Clarence Wilbur; Venes, Donald |title=Taber's cyclopedic medical dictionary |publisher=F a Davis Co |location= |year=2009 |pages=2366 |isbn=0-8036-1559-0}}</ref>

==Use in triage==
[[Image:RTS Fast Ref Chart.jpg|240px|thumb]]
The Revised Trauma Score is made up of a three categories: [[Glasgow Coma Scale]], [[Systole (medicine)|Systolic]] blood pressure, and respiratory rate. The score range is 0-12.  In [[Simple triage and rapid treatment|START]] [[triage]], a patient with an RTS score of 12 is labeled delayed, 11 is urgent , and 10-3 is immediate. Those who have an RTS below 3 are declared dead and should not receive certain care because they are highly unlikely to survive without a significant amount of resources.{{cn|date=December 2012}}

